'''Charles Ferdinand Pahud de Mortanges''' (born [[May 13]], [[1896]] in [[The Hague]] - died [[April 7]], [[1971]] in [[The Hague]]) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[Equestrianism|horse rider]]  who competed in the [[1924 Summer Olympics]], in the [[1928 Summer Olympics]], in the [[1932 Summer Olympics]], and in the [[1936 Summer Olympics]].

In the [[1924 Summer Olympics]] he won the gold medal in the [[Equestrian at the 1924 Summer Olympics|team three-day event]] and placed fourth in the [[Equestrian at the 1924 Summer Olympics|individual three-day event]].

Four years later he won the gold medals in the [[Equestrian at the 1928 Summer Olympics|team three-day event]] as well as in the [[Equestrian at the 1928 Summer Olympics|individual three-day event]].

In 1932 he won again the gold medal in the [[Equestrian at the 1932 Summer Olympics|individual three-day event]] and the silver medal in the [[Equestrian at the 1932 Summer Olympics|team three-day event]].

At the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] he was not able to finish the [[Equestrian at the 1936 Summer Olympics|individual three-day event]] and also the Dutch team failed to place in the [[Equestrian at the 1936 Summer Olympics|team three-day event]].

